PL/1 BASICS:
============

- PL/1 is a legacy high level procedure language suitable for commercial, engineering and scientific application.
- PL/1 main domains are data processing, numerical computation, scientific calculation and system program.

- PL/1 Program Structure:
 - Every PL/1 application is collection of load modules which has one or more compilation units.
 - A compilation unit maybe a PL/1 package or an external procedure.
 - Each package can contain 0 or more procedures
 - PL/1 is a block structure language, procedure can contain zero or more blocks
 - Blocks can be either procedure block or begin block
 - Block may have 0 or more groups
 - Groups are collection of statements which can be either executed or bypassed
 - Statements are collection of identifiers, Delimiters, Operators, Constants
 - Final indivisible part of PL/1 is characters

Application
 └── Load Modules ()
     └── Compilation Units (a single PL/1 program)
         ├── Package
         │    └── Procedures
         │         └── Blocks
         │              └── Groups
         │                   └── Statements
         │                        └── Characters
         └── External Procedure

- Features of PL/1:
 - High level procedural language
 - It's free form language with no reserved words
 - Block oriented language consisting elements like packages, begin blocks and statements, this type of structure allows programmer to produce highly modular applications
 - It consist of several built-in functions like arithmetic, mathematical, array handling, string handling, condition handling, storage control.
 - Dynamic memory allocation, it contains built-in functions to allocate and de-allocate memory at runtime
 - Powerful exception handling facilities

- PL/1 Coding structure:
 - Columns
- 1 : Reserved for use by OS
  - 2-72: Code PL/1 statements
- 73-80: System generated number which is ignored by compiler

- PL/1 Program:
