DIFFERENT TYPES OF PROCEDURES:
==============================
- Procedure will have a block of statement delimited by a procedure statement and a corresponding end statement.

- The Procedure statement identifies the procedure as main, subroutine or function based on the parameters given to the procedure

- Types of procedure:
 - Main Procedure
LABEL: PROC OPTION(MAIN);

 - Subroutine Procedure
LABEL: PROC(PARAMETERS);

 - Function Procedure
LABEL: PROC(PARAMETERS) RETURNS(ATTRIBUTES);

DEMO04: PROCEDURE OPTION(MAIN);
/*
FACT function, its definition is not coded within DEMO04 so its considered as external procedure.
DCL FACT EXTERNAL: Denotes it is external procedure
ENTRY(FIXED): Denotes the passing argument is of fixed decimal data type
RETURNS(FIXED): Denotes returning value data type is fixed decimal
*/
DCL FACT EXTERNAL ENTRY(FIXED) RETURNS(FIXED);
DCL NUM FIXED DECIMAL;
DCL FACTORIAL FIXED DECIMAL;

/*Invoking Function procedure*/
FACTORIAL=FACT(NUM);
DCL A FIXED DECIMAL(3,0) INIT(10),
   B FIXED DECIMAL(3,0) INIT(20);

/*Invoking Subroutine procedure*/
CALL SWAP(A,B);
PUT SKIP LIST('AFTER SWAP');
PUT SKIP LIST('A: '||A);
PUT SKIP LIST('B: '||B);

/*
It's an internal procedure
OPTION(BYADDR): Denotes actual parameters A & B, shares the same address as formal parameter A1 & B1
*/
SWAP: PROC(A1,B1) OPTION(BYADDR);
DCL (A1,B1,TEMP) FIXED DECIMAL(3,0);
TEMP=A1;
A1=B1;
B1=TEMP;
END SWAP;

END DEMO04;

-------------------------------------

/*Stored as a PDS member*/
FACT: PROC(NUM) RETURNS(FIXED);
DCL (NUM,I,RES) FIXED;
RES=1;
DO I=1 TO NUM BY 1;
RES=RES*I; 
END; 
RETURN(RES);
END FACT;

