STORAGE CLASSES:
================
- Storage class specifies for a variable determines the scope of the variable, i.e. disability and the time at which memory is allocated or de-allocated.
- Memory is allocated before the execution of the program for Automatic and Static storage class
- Memory is allocated after the execution of the program for Controlled and Based storage class
- PL1 supports 4 storages classes:
  - Automatic storage class
- Memory is allocated for a variable upon each entry to the block that contains variable declaration
- Memory is de-allocated when the execution of that block terminates
- Default storage class for variable declared within procedures
- Variables can also be declared using AUTOMATIC/AUTO attribute
- DCL A1 CHAR(10) AUTO;

  - Static storage class
- Memory is allocated before the start of execution of the program i.e. at the time of loading and freed at the end of execution 
- Default storage class for
 - Variables declared within a package but outside any level-1 procedure
 - Variables implicitly or explicitly declared with EXTERNAL attribute
- Variables are declared as static variables using STATIC attribute
- DCL A1 FIXED DECIMAL(15,2) STATIC;

  - Controlled storage class
- Controlled storage variables are allocated memory explicitly within the program using ALLOCATE statement and released by FREE statement
- Controlled storage variable are declared using CONTROLLED attribute
- DCL A1 CHAR(100) VARYING CTL;

  - Based storage class (Pointer)
- Memory is dynamically allocated and de-allocated for a based storage variable
- Based storage variables are declared using BASED attribute
- Address of a based storage variable is stored in a pointer
- Pointer are declared using POINTER attribute
- DCL PTR POINTER;
 DCL AMOUNT FLOAT BIN(10) BASED(PTR);

